---

<InternWiki title={title} description={description} category={category} order={order}>
	<h2>Cross-Firm Networking</h2>
	<p>Your firm's internal intern class provides a baseline social network, but expanding your connections across other firms maximizes the utility of your summer in New York. The finance, consulting, and tech industries operate in highly interconnected ecosystems.</p>
	
	<h3>Structured Events</h3>
	<p>Leverage structured intern events designed to aggregate young professionals. Many large banks and consulting firms host open networking mixers that permit plus-ones. Secure invitations through your existing university network. University alumni associations located in NYC also host dedicated summer welcome events for current students and recent graduates.</p>

	<h2>Organic Socializing</h2>
	<p>Organic networking requires occupying the physical spaces where interns congregate after hours.</p>
	
	<ul>
		<li><strong>The Financial District:</strong> Bars along Stone Street, such as Ulysses, serve as the primary after-work aggregation point for Wall Street interns on Thursdays and Fridays.</li>
		<li><strong>The East Village:</strong> Establishments like The 13th Step or Phebe's attract large crowds of recent graduates and interns seeking high-energy nightlife.</li>
		<li><strong>Recreational Sports:</strong> Join a ZogSports or Volo summer league. These leagues group free agents onto teams and mandate post-game bar visits. This forces interaction with young professionals outside of your immediate industry.</li>
	</ul>
</InternWiki>
